AB  - Lucille Clifton has been a steady, if often unacknowledged, champion of the New Body, proudly showcasing in her poetry the fat black body as a force of resistance against the oppressive effects of racism, sexism, ageism, ableism, and classism that join ranks to beleaguer black women. In this article, Henneberg focuses on Clifton's response to the pervasive Western imperative to be thin -- a destructive phenomenon that is frequently identified as a natural and necessary reaction to the rise in obesity but is, in fact, more aptly labeled the modern epidemic of fat prejudice. Clifton's poetry never suggests that obesity in the First World is not real; indeed, few fat activists and scholars of obesity studies; instead, her poems take issue with common perceptions and valuations of fat.
