AN  - 1873856306
AB  - This article engages with John Gumperz's research legacy by examining his statements regarding indexicality at different stages in his career: the “Introduction” to Directions in Sociolinguistics (1972); a framing essay in Rethinking Linguistic Relativity (Gumperz, Introduction to Part IV, Cambridge University Press, 1996); and a recent series of interviews and essays in Language and Social Interaction (2002). Situating his evolving understanding of indexicality vis-á-vis other work in linguistic anthropology (Agha, Journal of Linguistic Anthropology 15: 38-59, 2005; Silverstein, Language & Communication 23: 193-229, 2003a; Urciuoli, Exposing prejudice: Puerto Rican experiences of race, class, and language, Westview, 1996), I discuss how indexical concepts such as “ordering,” when paired with concepts of spatio-temporal scale (Blommaert, Intercultural Pragmatics 4: 1-19, 2007), provide insightful ways of theorizing and analyzing the dynamics of globalization and language contact. The argument is developed via case studies of migration and multilingualism, based on fieldwork in Belgium (Blommaert et al., Language & Communication 25: 197-216, 2005a, Ethnography 6: 205-235, 2005b) and the United States (Collins and La Santa, Exploring ethnicity and class as communicative practice, 2007; Collins and Slembrouck, Goffman and globalization, Continuum, 2009).
